     4	# platform
     5	
     6	## Purpose
     7	OS abstraction layer. Provides platform detection, default socket directory resolution, process name lookup, the std.Io runtime wrapper used by the server control plane, and readiness backend glue (`kqueue` on macOS, `epoll` on Linux, `poll` fallback).
     8	
     9	## Key Files
    10	
    11	| File | Description |
    12	|------|-------------|
    13	| `platform.zig` | `Os` enum, `defaultSocketDir()`, `getProcessName()` with per-platform dispatch |
    14	| `std_io.zig` | `Runtime` u2014 `std.Io.Threaded` wrapper for the zmux control-plane runtime |
    15	| `poller.zig` | `Poller` u2014 readiness backend wrapper using `kqueue` / `epoll` / `poll` |
    16	
    17	## For AI Agents
    18	
    19	### Working In This Directory
    20	- Platform-specific code uses `builtin.os.tag` for conditional compilation
    21	- `platform.zig` is the unified entry point for helpers; keep the std.Io runtime wrapper and readiness poller small and reusable rather than reintroducing large bespoke event-loop stacks
    22	- Socket directory resolution: `$ZMUX_TMPDIR` > `$TMPDIR` > `/tmp`
    23	- Process name lookup: `proc_pidpath` on macOS, `/proc/<pid>/comm` on Linux
    24	
    25	### Testing Requirements
    26	- Platform-specific tests should be gated with `if (builtin.os.tag == .macos)` / `.linux`
    27	- The std.Io runtime wrapper should keep at least one focused test proving the Unix control-plane socket path works
    28	- The readiness poller should keep focused tests for readable-fd wakeups, gated per platform where needed
    29	
    30	## Dependencies
    31	
    32	### External
    33	- `std.Io.Threaded` from the Zig standard library
    34	- POSIX readiness APIs: `kqueue` on macOS, `epoll` on Linux, `poll` fallback elsewhere
